System & UI/UX Design Document
Project: Nexus-V
Objective: Define the visual language, database schemas, and API/WebSocket communication layer for the MVP.

1. UI/UX Visual Identity: "Precision Modernism"
To stand out, Nexus-V will avoid standard, boring corporate templates. It needs to feel like the dashboard of a high-end electric vehicle.

A. Global Styling (The Vibe)
Theme: Dark Mode Default. It reduces glare, saves battery (relevant for EV users), and makes brightly colored data metrics "pop."

Design Language: Glassmorphism. Semi-transparent, blurred backgrounds for cards and modals to give a sense of depth and hierarchy over a dark, sleek background.

Typography:

Headers: Orbitron or Montserrat (Bold, geometric, tech-forward).

Body/Data: Inter or Roboto Mono (Clean, highly legible for numbers and wait times).

B. Color Palette
Background: Deep Space Blue (#0B132B) transitioning to Void Black (#000000).

Primary Accent (Brand): Electric Cyan (#00F2FF). Used for active navigation, borders, and general highlights.

Functional Colors (The "Glance" System):

🟢 Success/Available: Neon Green (#39FF14) – EV slot open, queue joined.

🟡 Pending/Warning: Alert Amber (#FFB000) – Waiting in queue, pending mechanic approval.

🔴 Action Required/Offline: Crimson Red (#FF2A2A) – Broken charger, urgent brake replacement needed.

2. Database Schema (MongoDB / Mongoose)
Since you are dealing with distinct types of services (Washing, EV, Repair), a NoSQL database is perfect. Here is the MVP schema design.

A. User Collection (users)
Stores driver profiles and their active states.

JSON
{
  "_id": "ObjectId",
  "name": "String",
  "phone": "String",
  "vehicleType": "String (ICE | EV)",
  "activeQueueId": "ObjectId (null if not in queue)",
  "activeEVSlotId": "ObjectId (null if not booked)"
}
B. Partner Collection (partners)
Stores the garages, car washes, and charging stations.

JSON
{
  "_id": "ObjectId",
  "businessName": "String",
  "type": "String (WASH | REPAIR | EV_STATION)",
  "location": { "lat": "Number", "lng": "Number" },
  "status": "String (OPEN | CLOSED)",
  "metrics": {
     "currentQueueLength": "Number",
     "avgWaitTimeMins": "Number"
  }
}
C. Trust Engine Records (service_proofs)
The ledger for the mechanic's visual proof and user approval.

JSON
{
  "_id": "ObjectId",
  "partnerId": "ObjectId",
  "userId": "ObjectId",
  "imageUrl": "String (AWS S3 or Cloudinary link)",
  "description": "String (e.g., 'Worn out brake pads')",
  "estimatedCost": "Number",
  "status": "String (PENDING | APPROVED | REJECTED)",
  "timestamp": "Date"
}
D. EV Charging Slots (ev_slots)
Individual chargers tied to a specific partner location.

JSON
{
  "_id": "ObjectId",
  "stationId": "ObjectId",
  "hardwareId": "String",
  "status": "String (AVAILABLE | BOOKED | CHARGING | OFFLINE)",
  "bookedBy": "ObjectId (UserId, null if available)",
  "bookingExpiresAt": "Date (15 mins from booking)"
}
3. API & WebSocket Architecture
To achieve the "Zero Latency" feel, Nexus-V splits communication into REST (for static actions) and WebSockets (for live data).

A. REST API Endpoints (Express.js)
GET /api/partners/nearby?type=WASH&lat=...&lng=...

Action: Fetches a list of nearby service centers.

POST /api/trust/upload-proof

Action: Mechanic uploads an image. Hits the Python microservice for basic validation, stores it, and creates a service_proof record.

PATCH /api/trust/resolve-proof/:id

Action: User clicks "Approve" or "Reject". Updates the database and alerts the mechanic.

B. Real-Time Socket.io Events
This is the core of the app's "wow" factor during the demo.

Event: join_queue

Flow: User emits. Server adds them to the partner's queue array -> Server broadcasts queue_updated to all users viewing that garage to update the "Cars Ahead" counter instantly.

Event: ev_slot_reserved

Flow: User emits. Server marks slot as BOOKED and starts the 15-minute TTL (Time-To-Live). Server broadcasts station_status_change so the charger turns "Yellow" on everyone else's map.

Event: proof_received

Flow: Triggered by the backend after a mechanic uploads a photo. Pushes a real-time notification to the specific User's app: "Action Required: Review Brake Pad Cost."

4. The Python Microservice (The "Trust" Validator)
While the main backend is Node.js, your Python service runs independently.

Input: Receives an image from the Node backend.

Process: Uses OpenCV/Pillow to check image validity (e.g., rejecting pitch-black images or heavily blurred photos before sending them to the user).

Output: Returns a boolean (isValid: true/false) back to Node.js.